<h3>cHAPTER 3 uNICODE AND THE CHAR tYPE</h3>
<p>When Java was originally designed, it was anticipated that any Unicode character would fit in 2 bytes (16 bits), so char and Character were designed accordingly. In fact, a Unicode character can now require up to 4 bytes. Thus, UTF-16, the internal Java encoding, requires supplementary characters use 2 code units. 
Characters in the Basic Multilingual Plane (the most common ones) still use 1. A Java char is used for each code unit.</p>
<p>Unicode was invented to overcome the lomitation of traditional character encoding scheme , Before Unicode there are many different standard like ASCII for USA , ISO 8859-1 for Western European Countries </p>
<p>A Particular code value represents different letters in different languages More ever languages with more character sets have variable lengths </p>
<p>Around 1980 for purpose of internationalization all other standard are unified into one at that time it is thought that around 16 bit or 65536 characters are more than enough to represent all characters</p>
<p>but with time these remain not enough to cope with all characters</p>
<p>How java handle this , Code point are introduced for this purpose , Code point are written in Hexadecimal format prefixed with U+ such as for Latin Letter A Unicode is U+0041 </p>
<p>Unicode has code points that are grouped into 17 code plane  </p>
<p>The first code plane called basic multilingual plane contains all 16 bit characters or approx 65000 characters , Unicode characters 
from U+0000 to U+FFFF . Sixteen additional planes with code points U+100000 to U+10FFFF holds the supplementary characters</p>
<p>The UTF-16 encoding represents all Unicode code points in a variable length code . The characters in the basic multi lingual plane are represented as 16 bit value called code points </p>
<p>The supplementary characters are encoded as consecutive pair of code units. The supplement characters are encoded as consecutive pair of code units</p>
<p>Each of the value in such a encoding pair is falling in the range of 2048 unused value of the multi lingual plane , called surrogates area (U+D800 to U+DBFF) belongs to first code unit  and U+DC00 to U+DFFF 
to second code point </p>
<p>This is rather clever because you can immediately tell whether code point unit encodes a single character or its the first or second part of 
supplementary character </p>
<p>For example there is a mathematical symbol octonions  has a code point U+1D546 and is encoded by two code units U+D835 and U+DD46 see  http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/UTF-16</p>
<p>In Java, the char type describes a code unit in the UTF-16 encoding.
Our strong recommendation is not to use the char type in your programs unless you are actually manipulating UTF-16 code units. You are almost always better off treating strings as abstract data types.</p>

